        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_3",
          "href": null,
          "name": "55a4",
          "text": "“Money has become a ring we wear through the nose, which allows us to be led around by those who control it.”",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 109,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 0,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "PQ"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_4",
          "href": null,
          "name": "46de",
          "text": "— Mark Kinney",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "PQ"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_5",
          "href": null,
          "name": "9718",
          "text": "Money is one of the core technologies at the heart of human societies. It is the means by which we trade among ourselves. In many if not most modern societies money has become a central element around which many human relationships are organised.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_6",
          "href": null,
          "name": "c8d9",
          "text": "To ask what money is may seem a trivial question that is barely worth asking. After all, we make constant use of it in our day-to-day lives and, for the most part, pay it no attention whatever — other than to occasionally worry whether we have enough of it. Our unquestioned assumption is that it is a neutral lubricant for the economic system that in no way influences how that system works. We also tend to assume that money works today the way it has always worked.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_7",
          "href": null,
          "name": "45fd",
          "text": "These and most other common assumptions about money, in fact, are mistaken. Today’s unitary money systems covering nations and regions are very much the exception in historical terms. While empires at various stages of history have had currencies covering large areas, locally-based money systems — sometimes working alongside the imperial currency, often alone and in the absence of an imperial currency — have been much more the norm.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_8",
          "href": null,
          "name": "c6d2",
          "text": "The first US dollar was minted in 1792 and initially the early member states of the USA all issued their own version (more). Before its introduction there were at least 7,000 different currencies in operation in the US (Dawson, 2009). The first people of North-America were trading amongst tribes in a variety of currencies and through barter.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 122,
              "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Early_American_currency",
              "rel": "noopener",
              "start": 118,
              "title": "",
              "anchorType": "LINK",
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "A",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_9",
          "href": null,
          "name": "ce42",
          "text": "Many of the currencies used throughout recorded history have not taken the form of notes and coins. Systems of exchange have included beads, cowrie shells, cattle, cocoa beans, grain, wool, precious metals and many other materials and resources. Even today, the great majority of ‘money’ — typically over 90 per cent — is made up not of notes and coins, but rather never leaves the digitalised columns of the bank’s computer databases.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_10",
          "href": null,
          "name": "5685",
          "text": "Most people believe or used to believe — as a new awareness is spreading rapidly through social media — that all money today is created by governments. This is not the case. While governments declare a currency like the Euro, Pound, Yen or Dollar ‘legal tender’, the percentage they issue as paper and coin currency through their national minting and printing press is only a very small proportion of the money coming into circulation each year. More than 90 per cent of all money is created by banks in the form of debt, practically out of thin air.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 520,
              "href": null,
              "rel": null,
              "start": 501,
              "title": null,
              "anchorType": null,
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "EM",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_11",
          "href": null,
          "name": "ace3",
          "text": "Every time a loan is granted and a bank enters it into their books, the volume of money in the global economy grows a little. This money is entirely based on collective trust in that particular money system. Such currencies are referred to as Fiat Money, as they have been declared legal tender without being backed up by any physical commodity. The value of such fiat currencies is derived from the relationship between supply and demand rather than the value of the material the money is made of.",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
          "dropCapImage": null,
          "iframe": null,
          "layout": null,
          "markups": [
            {
              "end": 253,
              "href": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fiat_money",
              "rel": "",
              "start": 243,
              "title": "",
              "anchorType": "LINK",
              "linkMetadata": null,
              "type": "A",
              "name": null,
              "creatorIds": null
            }
          ],
          "type": "P"
        },
        {
          "id": "7f1e42ae4f92_12",
          "href": null,
          "name": "9121",
          "text": "",
          "metadata": null,
          "mixtapeMetadata": null,
          "hasDropCap": null,
